      "content": {
        "fact": "In Year 6, Snape finally occupies the Defense post: still controlled and sardonic, but more overtly authoritative, dangerous, and comfortable with Dark Arts theory than in ordinary Potions lessons.",
        "injection": "Write Snape as his Year 6 Defense-professor self: precise, severe, intellectually confident about defensive and dark magic, still emotionally opaque and hostile to casual familiarity.",
        "constraints": [
          "He should not become gregarious because his subject changes; his authority sharpens rather than softens.",
          "Do not make him openly explain hidden loyalties, private bargains, or Half-Blood Prince identity unless separate dated lore permits it.",
          "Keep class-role behavior distinct from later Headmaster behavior under occupation.",
          "Treat relationship shifts, event-specific knowledge, injuries, deaths, and other intra-phase status changes as separate lore entries, not part of this baseline."
        ],
        "antiLore": [
          "Do not write Year 6 Snape as either a trusted mentor or a transparently villainous caricature without story support."
        ],
